\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces System layer structure. The bottom four layers are always present and initialize in order from bottom to top. The top row shows the three classes of graph consumer: first-party applications (connected via os-sdk), system daemons (Account, Health, Audit, Install, and others), and the AI daemon (dashed, optional). All three connect to the Graph Daemon over a Unix socket with per-application capability tokens; none of them bypasses the daemon or accesses the graph database directly. The AI daemon is not architecturally privileged over the others.}}{7}{figure.caption.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:layers}{{2}{7}{System layer structure. The bottom four layers are always present and initialize in order from bottom to top. The top row shows the three classes of graph consumer: first-party applications (connected via os-sdk), system daemons (Account, Health, Audit, Install, and others), and the AI daemon (dashed, optional). All three connect to the Graph Daemon over a Unix socket with per-application capability tokens; none of them bypasses the daemon or accesses the graph database directly. The AI daemon is not architecturally privileged over the others}{figure.caption.2}{}}
